definition.value: A monocarboxylic acid amide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of any fatty acid with the amino group of taurine.
A fatty acid-taurine conjugate derived from stearic acid.
Any monounsaturated fatty acid containing 20 carbons and 1 double bond.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid containing 20 carbons and 4 double bonds.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid containing 20 carbons and 5 double bonds.
A 1-(alk-1-enyl)-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion in which the alk-1-enyl and acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 contain 36 carbon atoms in total with 3 additional double bonds.
A 1-(alk-1-enyl)-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion in which the alk-1-enyl and acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 contain 36 carbon atoms in total with 4 additional double bonds.
A 1-(alk-1-enyl)-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion in which the alk-1-enyl and acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 contain 38 carbon atoms in total with 5 additional double bonds.

A reagent that lightens or whitens a substrate through chemical reaction. Bleaching reactions usually involve oxidative or reductive processes that degrade colour systems. Bleaching can occur by destroying one or more of the double bonds in the conjugated chain, by cleaving the conjugated chain, or by oxidation of one of the other moieties in the conjugated chain. Their reactivity results in many bleaches having strong bactericidal, disinfecting, and sterilising properties.
A member of the class of lysophosphatidic acids obtained by hydrolytic removal of one of the two acyl groups of any phosphatidic acid. A 'closed' class.
An octadecenoate in which the double bond is at C-9.
A dicarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of at least one of the carboxy groups of oxalic acid.
An organic anion obtained by deprotonation of at least one of the acidic groups of 3-phosphoglyceric acid.
A primary ammonium ion obtained by protonation of the amino group of 5-aminolevulinic acid.
A peptide cation obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group and protonation of the amino and guanidino groups of bradykinin; major species at pH 7.3.
A drug that makes increases the sensitivity of tumour cells to radiation therapy.
A steroid sulfate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of at least one of the sulfo groups of 5alpha-pregnan-3beta,20alpha-diol disulfate
A steroid sulfate that is 5alpha-pregnane-3beta,20alpha-diol in which both hydroxy hydrogens have been replaced by sulfo groups.
A 5alpha-pregnane-3beta,20alpha-diol disulfate anion obtained by deprotonation of both sulfo groups of 5alpha-pregnane-3beta,20alpha-diol disulfate.
An acyl-CoA oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate, diphosphate and carboxy groups of any omega-carboxyacyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A carboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of any dicarboxylic acid that contains no carbon-carbon double bonds.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of any oxo dicarboxylic acid.
An O-acylcarnitine in which the R is a saturated fatty acyl chain.
An O-acylcarnitine in which the R is a monounsaturated fatty acyl chain.
An L-alpha-amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of L-lysine; major species at pH 7.3.
A hydroxy polyunsaturated fatty acid anion consisting of icosatrieonate anion carrying one or more hydroxy substituents.
A 1-(alk-1-enyl)-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion in which the alkenyl and acyl groups are specified as (1Z)-hexadecenyl and linoleoyl respectively.
A non-proteinogenic alpha-amino acid that is tryptophan in which the hydrogen at position 5 on the indole ring is replaced by a bromo group.
An alpha-amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of 5-bromotryptophan; major species at pH 7.3.
A tricarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of at least one of the carboxy groups of citric acid.
An alpha-amino-acid cation obtained by protonation of any dimethylarginine.
A HODE(1-) that is the conjugate base of 13-HODE, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A HODE(1-) that is the conjugate base of 9-HODE, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
Abbreviation for nicotinamide-adenine dinucleotide when its oxidation state is unknown or unspecified. It is used in metabolic pathways like glycolysis and citric acid cycle.
A coenzyme that may be NAD(+) or NADP(+).
A coenzyme that may be NADH or NADPH.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid anion carrying one or more hydroperoxy substituents.
Any organic compound having an initial boiling point less than or equal to 250 degreeC (482 degreeF) measured at a standard atmospheric pressure of 101.3 kPa.
An alkanesulfonate in which the carbon at position 1 is attached to R, which can represent hydrogens, a carbon chain, or other groups.
Any phenol carrying an additional methoxy substituent at the ortho-position.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 35 carbons in total with 1 double bond.
An alcohol where the hydroxy group is attached to a saturated carbon atom adjacent to a double bond (R groups may be H, organyl, etc.).
An allylic alcohol in which the carbon atom that links the double bond to the hydroxy group is also attached to two hydrogens.
An allylic alcohol in which the carbon atom that links the double bond to the hydroxy group is also attached to one other carbon and one hydrogen.
A phosphorus oxoanion resulting from the removal of one proton from the phosphonic acid group of tenofovir. The major microspecies at pH 7.3.
An L-cysteine derivative obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of any long-chain fatty acid with the side-chain thiol group of L-cysteine.
A UDP-amino sugar having alpha-D-glucosamine as the amino-sugar component.
